  </head>
  <body>
    <button id="theme-toggle" title="Toggle dark mode">🌙 Dark Mode</button>    <div class="video-container"> <iframe src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/0R0z73Xj7_s"

        title="Basic Life Support (BLS) Overview | PLAB2/UKMLA Essentials" allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture; web-share"

        referrerpolicy="strict-origin-when-cross-origin" allowfullscreen="" frameborder="0"></iframe>
    </div>
    <h3>BASIC LIFE SUPPORT (BLS) OVERVIEW &amp; TEACHING GUIDE</h3>
    <h4>A. SCENARIO &amp; INITIAL APPROACH (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0R0z73Xj7_s&amp;t=20s">Video
        0:20</a>)</h4>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Typical Task:</strong> Demonstrate and teach BLS steps to a
        junior doctor (e.g., Alex, an FY1) who has not attended a BLS workshop,
        then assess and provide feedback. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0R0z73Xj7_s&amp;t=27s">Video
          0:27-0:47</a>)</li>
      <li><strong>Resource Availability:</strong> A Resuscitation Council UK
        chart will likely be present in the cubicle, which can be used as a
        reference. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0R0z73Xj7_s&amp;t=57s">Video
          0:57-1:06</a>)</li>
      <li><strong>Initial Interaction (Rapport &amp; Assessment):</strong> (<a class="timestamp"

          href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0R0z73Xj7_s&amp;t=74s">Video
          1:14-1:41</a>)
        <ul>
          <li>Build rapport.</li>
          <li>Assess their existing knowledge of BLS.</li>
          <li>Understand what they want to learn.</li>
          <li>Briefly discuss why BLS is performed and on which patients.</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
    </ul>
    <h4>B. FUNDAMENTALS OF BLS (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0R0z73Xj7_s&amp;t=105s">Video
        1:45</a>)</h4>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Purpose:</strong> To be the heart and lungs in an unconscious
        patient who is not breathing properly. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0R0z73Xj7_s&amp;t=107s">Video
          1:47-2:05</a>)</li>
      <li><strong>Key Components: </strong>(<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0R0z73Xj7_s&amp;t=109s">Video
          1:49-1:51</a>) </li>
      <ul>
        <li>Chest compressions and </li>
        <li>rescue breaths. </li>
      </ul>
      <li><strong>UK Resuscitation Guidelines (Important Note):</strong> Pulse
        check is NOT part of the UK BLS guidelines for lay rescuers/initial BLS.
        (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0R0z73Xj7_s&amp;t=128s">Video
          2:08-2:25</a>)</li>
    </ul>
    <h4>C. ADULT BLS STEPS (DRS ABC or DOCTORS ABC) (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0R0z73Xj7_s&amp;t=155s">Video
        2:35</a>)</h4>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>D - Danger:</strong> (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0R0z73Xj7_s&amp;t=159s">Video
          2:39-2:43</a>)
        <ul>
          <li>Assess the scene for any danger to yourself, the victim, or
            bystanders. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0R0z73Xj7_s&amp;t=163s">Video
              2:43-2:47</a>)</li>
          <li>If danger is present (e.g., middle of the road, fire), move the
            victim to a safe place before starting BLS. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0R0z73Xj7_s&amp;t=167s">Video
              2:47-3:02</a>) Ensure safety for all. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0R0z73Xj7_s&amp;t=181s">Video
              3:01-3:09</a>)</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li><strong>R - Response:</strong> (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0R0z73Xj7_s&amp;t=193s">Video
          3:13</a>)
        <ul>
          <li>Check for response by gently asking "Hello, can you hear me?" (<a

              class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0R0z73Xj7_s&amp;t=194s">Video
              3:14-3:18</a>)</li>
          <li>Gently tap the shoulders. Be gentle to avoid causing further
            injury. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0R0z73Xj7_s&amp;t=198s">Video
              3:18-3:35</a>)</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li><strong>S - Shout for Help:</strong> (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0R0z73Xj7_s&amp;t=217s">Video
          3:37-3:43</a>)
        <ul>
          <li>Call out for assistance from anyone nearby.</li>
        </ul>
        <p><br>
        </p>
        <ul>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li><strong>A - Airway:</strong> (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0R0z73Xj7_s&amp;t=223s">Video
          3:43-3:48</a>)
        <ul>
          <li>Open the airway using the head-tilt chin-lift maneuver. (<a class="timestamp"

              href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0R0z73Xj7_s&amp;t=228s">Video
              3:48-3:50</a>)</li>
          <li>If any visible foreign body is present, remove it. (<a class="timestamp"

              href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0R0z73Xj7_s&amp;t=230s">Video
              3:50-3:52</a>)</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li><strong>B - Breathing:</strong> (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0R0z73Xj7_s&amp;t=234s">Video
          3:54-3:57</a>)
        <ul>
          <li>Check for normal breathing for no more than 10 seconds. (<a class="timestamp"

              href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0R0z73Xj7_s&amp;t=255s">Video
              4:15-4:18</a>) Be quick. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0R0z73Xj7_s&amp;t=258s">Video
              4:18-4:22</a>)</li>
          <li>Use Look, Listen, and Feel: (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0R0z73Xj7_s&amp;t=238s">Video
              3:58-4:02</a>)
            <ul>
              <li><strong>Look</strong> for chest rise and fall. (<a class="timestamp"

                  href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0R0z73Xj7_s&amp;t=242s">Video
                  4:02</a>)</li>
              <li><strong>Listen</strong> for breath sounds. (<a class="timestamp"

                  href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0R0z73Xj7_s&amp;t=245s">Video
                  4:05</a>)</li>
              <li><strong>Feel</strong> for breath on your cheek. (<a class="timestamp"

                  href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0R0z73Xj7_s&amp;t=248s">Video
                  4:08-4:11</a>)</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li><strong>C - Call Emergency Services / Circulation (Compressions):</strong>
        <ul>
          <li>e.g., 999 or 2222 in a hospital). (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0R0z73Xj7_s&amp;t=262s">Video
              4:22-4:24</a>)</li>
          <li>Request an ambulance and an Automated External Defibrillator
            (AED). (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0R0z73Xj7_s&amp;t=268s">Video
              4:28-4:34</a>)</li>
          <li><strong>Start Chest Compressions:</strong> (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0R0z73Xj7_s&amp;t=277s">Video
              4:37-4:43</a>)
            <ul>
              <li>Use the heel of your dominant hand on the lower half of the
                sternum. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0R0z73Xj7_s&amp;t=283s">Video
                  4:43-4:48</a>)</li>
              <li>Interlock fingers of the other hand on top. (<a class="timestamp"

                  href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0R0z73Xj7_s&amp;t=288s">Video
                  4:48-4:51</a>)</li>
              <li>Keep elbows straight; pressure should come from the shoulders.
                (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0R0z73Xj7_s&amp;t=291s">Video
                  4:51-4:57</a>)</li>
              <li>Compress the chest to a depth of at least 1/3 of the chest
                diameter. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0R0z73Xj7_s&amp;t=299s">Video
                  4:59-5:03</a>)</li>
              <li>Allow full chest recoil between compressions. (<a class="timestamp"

                  href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0R0z73Xj7_s&amp;t=306s">Video
                  5:06-5:08</a>)</li>
              <li>Do not lift hands from the chest during compressions. (<a class="timestamp"

                  href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0R0z73Xj7_s&amp;t=308s">Video
                  5:08-5:12</a>)</li>
              <li>Count compressions aloud. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0R0z73Xj7_s&amp;t=312s">Video
                  5:12-5:15</a>)</li>
              <li>Perform 30 chest compressions. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0R0z73Xj7_s&amp;t=318s">Video
                  5:18-5:23</a>)</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li><strong>Rescue Breaths:</strong> (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0R0z73Xj7_s&amp;t=326s">Video
              5:26-5:28</a>)
            <ul>
              <li>Perform head-tilt chin-lift again. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0R0z73Xj7_s&amp;t=328s">Video
                  5:28-5:30</a>)</li>
              <li>Pinch the patient's nose. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0R0z73Xj7_s&amp;t=330s">Video
                  5:30-5:35</a>)</li>
              <li>Give mouth-to-mouth resuscitation. Deliver a normal breath
                (not forceful) until you see chest rise. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0R0z73Xj7_s&amp;t=335s">Video
                  5:35-5:43</a>)</li>
              <li>Allow chest to fall, then deliver a second breath. (<a class="timestamp"

                  href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0R0z73Xj7_s&amp;t=343s">Video
                  5:43-5:48</a>)</li>
              <li><em>Exam note: You may be asked to verbally explain rescue
                  breaths rather than demonstrate, or use a sheet over the
                  dummy's face. Follow instructions given.</em> (<a class="timestamp"

                  href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0R0z73Xj7_s&amp;t=348s">Video
                  5:48-6:12</a>)</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li><strong>Continue CPR:</strong> 30 compressions to 2 rescue breaths
            (30:2 ratio). (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0R0z73Xj7_s&amp;t=460s">Video
              7:40-7:43</a>)</li>
          <li><strong>AED Arrival:</strong> As soon as the AED arrives, switch
            it on and follow its voice/visual prompts. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0R0z73Xj7_s&amp;t=466s">Video
              7:46-7:51</a>)</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
    </ul>
    <h4>D. PEDIATRIC BLS CONSIDERATIONS (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0R0z73Xj7_s&amp;t=546s">Video
        9:06</a>)</h4>
    <ul>
      <li>Two protocols: Out-of-hospital and In-hospital. (<a class="timestamp"

          href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0R0z73Xj7_s&amp;t=548s">Video
          9:08-9:16</a>) The exam will specify which to teach. (<a class="timestamp"

          href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0R0z73Xj7_s&amp;t=570s">Video
          9:30-9:58</a>)</li>
      <li><strong>Out-of-Hospital Pediatric BLS:</strong> (<a class="timestamp"

          href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0R0z73Xj7_s&amp;t=598s">Video
          9:58</a>)
        <ul>
          <li>Designed to be simple, similar to adult BLS for lay rescuers. (<a

              class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0R0z73Xj7_s&amp;t=602s">Video
              10:02-10:10</a>)</li>
          <li>Check responsiveness, shout for help, open airway, check
            breathing. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0R0z73Xj7_s&amp;t=628s">Video
              10:28-10:33</a>)</li>
          <li><strong>Give 5 initial rescue breaths FIRST.</strong> Pediatric
            collapse is often respiratory in origin. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0R0z73Xj7_s&amp;t=637s">Video
              10:37-10:52</a>) These 5 breaths are only given at the beginning.
            (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0R0z73Xj7_s&amp;t=666s">Video
              11:06-11:20</a>)</li>
          <li>Then, continue with <strong>30 chest compressions to 2 rescue
              breaths (30:2).</strong> (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch%0A%20%20v=0R0z73Xj7_s&amp;t=672s">Video
              11:12-11:16, 10:10-10:12, 10:24</a>)</li>
          <li><strong>Calling for help (single rescuer):</strong> If alone,
            perform CPR for 1 minute before going to call emergency services
            (unless phone with speaker is available for earlier call). (<a class="timestamp"

              href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0R0z73Xj7_s&amp;t=689s">Video
              11:29-11:50</a>)</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li><strong>In-Hospital Pediatric BLS (for healthcare professionals):</strong>
        (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0R0z73Xj7_s&amp;t=726s">Video
          12:06</a>)
        <ul>
          <li>Call for help using hospital emergency number (e.g., 2222). (<a class="timestamp"

              href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0R0z73Xj7_s&amp;t=736s">Video
              12:16-12:28</a>)</li>
          <li>Follow similar initial steps (responsiveness, airway, breathing).</li>
          <li>Give 5 initial rescue breaths. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0R0z73Xj7_s&amp;t=752s">Video
              12:32</a>)</li>
          <li>Then, continue with <strong>15 chest compressions to 2 rescue
              breaths (15:2).</strong> (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0R0z73Xj7_s&amp;t=753s">Video
              12:33-12:43</a>)</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li><strong>Chest Compression Technique for Children/Infants:</strong>
        <ul>
          <li>Child (approx 1 year to puberty): One hand may be sufficient if
            the 1/3 chest depth can be achieved. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0R0z73Xj7_s&amp;t=791s">Video
              13:11-13:18</a>)</li>
          <li>Infant (under 1 year): Two fingers may be used for compressions. (<a

              class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0R0z73Xj7_s&amp;t=798s">Video
              13:18-13:25</a>)</li>
          <li>The aim is always to compress the chest by at least one-third of
            its depth. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0R0z73Xj7_s&amp;t=805s">Video
              13:25-13:32</a>)</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
    </ul>
    <h4>E. ASSESSING THE LEARNER &amp; PROVIDING FEEDBACK (<a class="timestamp"

        href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0R0z73Xj7_s&amp;t=377s">Video 6:17</a>)</h4>
    <ul>
      <li>After explaining, ask the student (Alex) to demonstrate the BLS steps.
        (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0R0z73Xj7_s&amp;t=379s">Video
          6:19-6:21</a>)</li>
      <li>Observe their performance. They will likely make a mistake or two. (<a

          class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0R0z73Xj7_s&amp;t=383s">Video
          6:23-6:27</a>)</li>
      <li><strong>Correcting Mistakes:</strong> (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0R0z73Xj7_s&amp;t=387s">Video
          6:27-6:29</a>)
        <ul>
          <li>Correct constructively and politely. Avoid sounding accusatory. (<a

              class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0R0z73Xj7_s&amp;t=391s">Video
              6:31-6:32</a>)</li>
          <li>Example: If student bends elbows during compressions: "Alex,
            you're doing good, a very good job. But you know, when you're doing
            the chest compression, make sure you don't bend the elbow. The force
            should be coming from the shoulder... Let's give another try.
            Perfect, you're doing good now." (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0R0z73Xj7_s&amp;t=395s">Video
              6:35-7:02</a>)</li>
          <li>Encourage and correct them as they perform. (<a class="timestamp"

              href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0R0z73Xj7_s&amp;t=500s">Video
              8:20-8:30</a>)</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
    </ul>
    <h4>F. WHEN TO STOP BLS (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0R0z73Xj7_s&amp;t=474s">Video
        7:54</a>)</h4>
    <ul>
      <li>The patient shows signs of life (e.g., starts breathing normally,
        moving). (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0R0z73Xj7_s&amp;t=479s">Video
          7:59-8:01</a>) - If so, place in recovery position. (<a class="timestamp"

          href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v_%0A%20%20=0R0z73Xj7_s&amp;t=481s">Video
          8:01-8:03</a>)</li>
      <li>Qualified help arrives and takes over. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0R0z73Xj7_s&amp;t=483s">Video
          8:03-8:05</a>)</li>
      <li>You become exhausted and unable to continue. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0R0z73Xj7_s&amp;t=488s">Video
          8:08-8:10</a>)</li>
    </ul>
    <p><em>Always refer to the Resuscitation Council UK chart provided during
        the exam for specific guidelines and sequences.</em> (<a class="timestamp"

        href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0R0z73Xj7_s&amp;t=798s">Video
        13:18-13:25</a>)</p>
    <script src="harsha_iframe_youtube_player.js"></script>
      <script src="theme-toggle.js"></script>
  </body>
</html>
